"schema_version": "v1",
"orchestration_decision": "execute_locally",
"decision_notes": "Synthesizing the Trie-based greedy strategy. The problem requires ensuring no ID is a prefix of another. This is equivalent to ensuring that in a Trie of the final IDs, every original ID ends at a leaf node. The optimal strategy is to process the Trie bottom-up: for any node that is marked as an 'end-of-ID', if it has children, we must 'push' that ID down to a leaf. However, the problem allows appending bits. A more efficient way to view this is: for every node in the Trie that is an end-of-ID, if it is not a leaf, we must extend it. But we can't just extend it to any leaf; we must ensure we don't create new prefix conflicts. The actual optimal strategy is: for every node that is an end-of-ID, if it has descendants that are also end-of-IDs, we must extend the current ID. Actually, the rule is simpler: no ID can be a prefix of another. In a Trie, this means no 'end-of-ID' node can be an ancestor of another 'end-of-ID' node. To minimize bits, for every node that is an end-of-ID and has descendants, we must push it down to the nearest available leaf. Wait, the problem says we can append bits to the original IDs. If ID A is a prefix of ID B, we must append bits to A so it's no longer a prefix of B. The most efficient way is to find the deepest nodes that are 'end-of-ID' and ensure they are leaves. If a node is an end-of-ID and has children, we must extend it. The cost is the distance to the nearest leaf that doesn't violate other constraints. Actually, the greedy approach is: for each node in the Trie, count how many 'end-of-ID' markers are in its subtree. If a node is an 'end-of-ID' and has descendants, we must move it. A better way: A node is 'bad' if it is an end-of-ID and has at least one descendant that is also an end-of-ID. To fix a bad node, we must extend it. The cost is 1 bit to move it to a child. We repeat this until it's a leaf. But we want to minimize total bits. The correct approach: For each node in the Trie, let count(u) be the number of end-of-ID markers in the subtree of u. If u is an end-of-ID, it must be a leaf. If it's not a leaf, we must push it down. The total cost is sum (depth(leaf_where_we_pushed_u) - depth(u)). However, we can't just push to any leaf. We must push to a leaf such that we don't overlap. This is equivalent to: for every node u that is an end-of-ID, if it has k descendants that are also end-of-IDs, we need to ensure u is not a prefix. The simplest way to solve this: For each node u in the Trie, let f(u) be the number of end-of-ID markers in its subtree. If u is an end-of-ID, we must 'use up' one leaf in its subtree. If u is an end-of-ID and f(u) > 1"
}

